04643nam a22007095i 9780231553322DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020039638  a97802315533227 a10.7312/baue170642doi  a(DE-B1597)590369  a(OCoLC)1266228135  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBP171.5b.B3813 2021 4aBP171.5b.B3813 2021eb 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a297.09/042231 aBauer, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Culture of Ambiguity :bAn Alternative History of Islam /cThomas Bauer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tTranslators’ Note -- t1. Cultural Ambiguity -- t2. Does God Speak in Textual Variants? -- t3. Does God Speak Ambiguously? -- t4. The Blessing of Dissent -- t5. The Islamization of Islam -- t6. Language: A Serious Business and a Game -- t7. The Ambiguity of Sexual Desire -- t8. The Serene Look at the World -- t9. In Quest of Certainty -- tSonderwege -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Western imagination, Islamic cultures are dominated by dogmatic religious norms that permit no nuance. Those fighting such stereotypes have countered with a portrait of Islam’s medieval “Golden Age,” marked by rationality, tolerance, and even proto-secularism. How can we understand Islamic history, culture, and thought beyond this dichotomy?In this magisterial cultural and intellectual history, Thomas Bauer reconsiders classical and modern Islam by tracing differing attitudes toward ambiguity. Over a span of many centuries, he explores the tension between one strand that aspires to annihilate all uncertainties and establish absolute, uncontestable truths and another, competing tendency that looks for ways to live with ambiguity and accept complexity. Bauer ranges across cultural and linguistic ambiguities, considering premodern Islamic textual and cultural forms from law to Quranic exegesis to literary genres alongside attitudes toward religious minorities and foreigners. He emphasizes the relative absence of conflict between religious and secular discourses in classical Islamic culture, which stands in striking contrast to both present-day fundamentalism and much of European history. Bauer shows how Islam’s encounter with the modern West and its demand for certainty helped bring about both Islamicist and secular liberal ideologies that in their own ways rejected ambiguity—and therefore also their own cultural traditions.Awarded the prestigious Leibniz Prize, A Culture of Ambiguity not only reframes a vast range of Islamic history but also offers an interdisciplinary model for investigating the tolerance of ambiguity across cultures and eras.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmbiguity. 0aIslamy20th centuryxSocial aspects. 0aIslamic sociology. 0aReligious tolerancexIslam. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh1 aBiesterfeldt, Hinrich.1 aTunstall, Tricia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/baue1706440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553322/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK